Also important are the chaotic changes of regime in 1918-1920, the loss of independence in 1940, the terror of the Stalinist regime, the struggle for democracy in the 80s, Lithuania's participation in the NATO and the EU. Lithuania also experienced the economic pain of the transition period after independence. However, Lithuanians also experienced positive news; this was the culmination of national revival, success in sports and business. These were important events which inspired Lithuanians to believe in a bright future. There were many small and big victories and honors not considered significant at the time, but which influenced Lithuanians' views on the future.

Last but not least, in the past 100 years, Lithuania had to sustain many difficulties. Lithuania had to restore its statehood, defend against aggressors and restore democracy. Lithuania's progress is also significant because in 2004, Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia were the first countries to join NATO of the countries of the former Soviet Union. Also, in 2004, the Baltic States declared themselves collectively as the Baltic EU candidate.

Lithuania had many other victories, but the truth is that some victories were won at terrible costs. For instance, 35,600 Lithuanian volunteers laid down their lives, 170,000 soldiers were mobilized from occupied Lithuania, and more than 75,000 Lithuanians were killers killed during the Soviet terror.
